  "texts": [
    "The peak signal-to-noise ratio (PSNR) measures the ratio between the maximum possible value of the original signal such as an image sample and the maximum noise level, which is the difference between the original and a predicted (or compressed) version of the signal (Hore and Ziou 2010).",
    "In simpler terms, PSNR quantifies how much the quality of the original signal exceeds the errors introduced, such as during compression or transmission.",
    "A higher PSNR indicates a closer match to the original signal, suggesting higher quality with less noticeable errors.",
    "The Structural Similarity Index (SSIM) measures the similarity between two images by analyzing their luminance, contrast, and structural information (Hore and Ziou 2010).",
    "It evaluates how variations in these elements influence the perceived quality of the images, going beyond simple pixel-by-pixel comparisons."
  ],
